>If you want an idea on how this can get out of hand, see if you
>can scare up the book by William Friedman and his wife which showed
>how the many people who tried to prove Francis Bacon was really
>Shakespeare did so by "force-fitting" Shakespeare's works as
>Baconian ciphers.  I've only seen the book in fragments, but even the
>fragments show how easy it is to "self hoax" oneself if one allows
>"solutions" of the type you give.
>I don't have the exact title of the Friedmans' book, but it is 
>something like "The Shakespearean Ciphers Examined" or "The Baconian
>Shakespeare Ciphers Examined" or some such.  Can someone bail me out?

Did you know that Shakespeare also help translate the "King James" Bible.
The proof is in the 49th Psalm.  The 49th word from the begining of the Psalm
is "shake" and the 49 word from the end is "spear".  And King James ordered
the translation be made when Shakespeare was 49. So there. :-)

